social_posts.post_text:
Removal of the contents of the nasopalatine canal  to facilitate placement of a dental implant. 
In this case we removed the canal contents using an electrocautery and round carbide bur, then placed 100% autogenous bone scrapings from the mandibular ramus into the canal and the alveolar ridge reconstructed using the Khoury technique. 
Reasons to enucleate the canal in preparation for a bone graft or a dental implant include inadvertent perforation into the canal when creating an osteotomy for an implant, severe atrophy of the maxilla, and a large foramen that precludes placing an implant into the desired location along the bony ridge.
The nasopalatine canal is usually around 10-mm long and 4-mm wide and slants from the horizontal plane at a 66-degree angle.
Numerous case reports indicate there is usually no permanent loss of sensation of the anterior palate when a bone graft and/or a dental implant is placed into the nasopalatine canal

social_posts.post_text:
Dissection and neurectomy of the lingual nerve after a submandibular gland excision to avoid perineural invasion and skip metastasis from an adenoid cystic carcinoma with the possibility of seeding of tumor cells seeding the the base of skull and brain. 
Adenoid cystic carcinoma (ACC) is one of the most common malignant salivary gland tumors, comprising 10% of all salivary gland neoplasms, which is characterized by perineural invasion (PNI) strong invasiveness, and hematogenous metastasis. 
Currently, there are two prominent theories on the pathogenesis of PNI: one is the “path of low resistance” and the other is reciprocal signaling interactions. Due to the anatomical proximity between the salivary glands and some cranial nerves, such as the facial nerve, trigeminal nerve (LINGUAL), hypoglossal nerve, and glossopharyngeal nerve, the salivary glands have plenty of neural tissues. Some researchers hypothesize that the tumor cells grow along the neural tissues which serves as a conduit for their distant migration, whereas the other researchers believe that there are certain factor-based interactions between tumor cells and nerves, which provide a microenvironment suitable for tumor cell growth and proliferation around the nerves. In addition, many recent studies have suggested that cell signaling factors contribute to the interaction between tumor and nerve tissue; for example, by increasing the affinity of tumor cells for neural tissue. At present, the occurrence of neurotropic invasion is widely considered to involve a variety of microenvironmental regulatory factors, including chemokines and their receptors, brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) family proteins and their receptors, nerve growth factor (NGF) family proteins and their receptors, as well as matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) and PNI-related cells (such as macrophages, astrocytes, and Schwann cells).

Adenomatoid odontogenic tumour (AOT), called as the master of disguise, is a relatively uncommon distinct odontogenic neoplasm that was first described by Steensland in 1905. It accounts for 2.2–13% of all odontogenic tumours. It is also known as ‘two-thirds tumor because 2/3rd of cases occur in the maxilla, 2/3rd occur in young females, 2/3rd of the cases are associated with un-erupted teeth, and 2/3rd of the affected teeth are canines. 
This case presented in the mandible of a male patient and associated with an impacted premolar.

social_posts.post_text:
Selective neck dissection (anterolateral/ supraomohyoid) in conjunction with hemiglossectomy to remove a tongue cancer. 
The supraomohyoid neck dissection is a selective cervical node dissection that removes the contents of the submental and submandibular triangles (lymph node level I), the jugulodigastric and jugulo-omohyoid lymph node groups, and the lymph node-bearing tissues located anterior to the cutaneous branches of the cervical plexus and above the omohyoid muscle (lymph node levels II and III). The sternocleidomastoid muscle, the spinal accessory nerve, and the internal jugular vein are preserved.
